This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for the Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON, SEYMOUR AND SHEPPARTON

Flow levels from Lake Eildon are expected to remain around 17,000 ML/d across the weekend.
Releases from Goulburn Weir will be increasing from 20,500 ML/d to 23,000 ML/d.

The Goulburn River at Shepparton is currently at 9.71 metres and rising, above the minor flood level. The Goulburn River at Shepparton is expected to remain above the minor flood level (9.50 m) for the remainder of Saturday into Sunday. The river level may peak around 9.90 metres overnight Saturday into Sunday.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Some local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Watt Road and Raftery Road Shepparton start to flood at 8.75m.
  • Watts Road, between McClennan Street and Old Tip Road has been closed due to floodwater. 
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 08/10/2023 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Broken River downstream of Casey Weir to the Kialla area.

MODERATE FLOODING PEAKING AT ORRVALE

No significant rainfall has been observed since 9:00 am Friday.

Broken River downstream of Casey Weir:
  • Moderate flooding continuing downstream of Casey Weir.
  • The Broken River at Orrvale is currently at 7.78 metres and peaking, above the moderate flood level. The Broken River at Orrvale is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (7.20 m) during the remainder of Saturday and into Sunday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

Impacts in your area:

Due to combined flooding in the Broken River and the Seven Creeks, high River and Creek levels are causing flooding into low lying areas in the Kialla - Kialla West areas.

  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Local roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding. 
  • The Midland Highway at Stewarton has re-opened following floodwater. 
  • Archer Street between Oxbow Avenue and Kialla Lakes Drive and Gordon Drive have closed due to floodwaters
  • .For information on road closures go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/

For more information, check out the Shepperton, Mooroopna and Kialla Local Flood Guide find out your flood risk. It also has maps and information about being prepared, your Emergency Kit and what happens in and around this area when floods happen. Go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/plan-and-stay-safe/flood-guides/greater-shepparton-city-council

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Ovens Rivers downstream of Rocky Point between Whorouly to Wangaratta.

MODERATE FLOODING CONTINUING ALONG THE OVENS RIVER AT WANGARATTA

Minor flooding continues to ease along the King river at Docker Road bridge
 
Moderate flooding is continuing along the Ovens River at Wangaratta, where river levels are steady but continue to fall slowly.

No significant rainfall has been observed in the 24 hours to 9:00 am Saturday. No significant rainfall is forecast across the Ovens and King Rivers catchment over the next few days.

Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point:
  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.
  • The Ovens River at Wangaratta is currently at 12.60 metres and steady, above the moderate flood level (12.40 m). The Ovens River at Wangaratta is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (12.40 m) into Saturday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:

  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising or staying high near you.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation. 
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground if still needed.
  • If you are camping close to the Ovens River, you need to move and stay away until the river and access tracks clear. You may be at risk of flooding or your access road to safety cut by floodwater. 
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services .
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

Impacts in your area:

A Community Update meeting was streamed live over Facebook and recorded at 2pm Thursday. Due to current flooding closing roads etc this "virtual" meeting with the latest information, it has been recorded for further sharing. Please find attached a YouTube recording of this video: Wangaratta Video Update 5 Oct 2023

The Wangaratta Local Flood Guide is available to check your flood risk. It also has maps and information about how to get prepared, your Emergency Kit and what happens in and around Wangaratta when floods happen. Go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/plan-and-stay-safe/at-home

Impacts in and around Wangaratta:

  • Yogi's nose is now visible, with the river height of 12.47m this morning
  • At Moderate flood level in Wangaratta, flooding above floor level of a few low lying homes and sheds is likely to occur in a few locations. 
  • A small number of properties are likely to be impacted and access tracks and driveways possibly become flooded.
Road Closures: 

  • Many roads and bridges will still be closed due to flooding, especially the Great Alpine Rd at Yellow Creek near Wangaratta- travel via the Detour Road bypass. 
  • Oxley Flats Rd, some roads in the Whorouly area, possibly the Yarrawonga Road near Peechelba. 
  • For more information on road closures, see below and go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au/
Flood Levels in Wangaratta:

At 11.9m, Minor flood level :
Water up to Yogis Chin in APEX Park. Apex Park and farmland along the Ovens, King and possibly the Fifteen Mile Creek floodplains north, south and east of Wangaratta begin flooding. Bike paths and walking tracks around and downstream of Apex Park and the Northern Beaches are closed. Many riverside carparks are closed.

At 12.4m, Moderate flood level:
Water up to Yogis Mouth in APEX Park. Extensive flooding through Apex Park. Residents in Wilson and Parfitt Rd levees are advised to prepare to evacuate (Unless levee damage happens before this). Shallow flooding to Pinkerton Cres and backyards along Templeton St and Baker St. Widespread, deep flooding outside of the Parfitt Rd levee.
 
At 12.7m, Major level flood:
6 cm lower than the Dec 2010 flood. Water up to Yogi's nose in APEX Park. Extensive road closures, including: Wilson Rd (outside levee area), Peechelba Rd at Seven Bridges, River Rd, Markwood-Everton Rd, Milawa-Tarrawingee Rd, Markwood-Tarrawingee Rd, Billabong Dve, Oxley Flats Rd, Stamps Lane area. Widespread flooding around the airport and along the Ovens River flats north of Wangaratta to Peechelba and Bundalong and into the Stamps Lane area north of Wangaratta.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream.

  • The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging 0 mm in the upper part of the catchment as well as in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Friday 06 October 2023. 
  • No rainfall is forecast for the catchment for Saturday 07 October 2023.
  • Water levels of the Yarra River at various locations are rising in response to the rain over the past few days.
Yarra River from Millgrove to Coldstream:
  • The level of the Yarra River at Coldstream is currently at 4.90 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (4.00 metres) and falling. 
  • It is expected to drop below the Minor Flood Level (4.00 metres) tomorrow, Sunday 8th October.
Act now - take actions immediately to protect your life and property, and move to higher ground.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary. 
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:  
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Moderate flooding in the Yarra/Watts River catchment is expected to cause substantial inundation in the rural and/or urban areas, and disruption to traffic. Melba Highway at Yarra Glen has been impacted by floodwaters.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:  
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Moderate flooding in the Yarra/Watts River catchment is expected to cause substantial inundation in the rural and/or urban areas, and disruption to traffic. Melba Highway at Yarra Glen has been impacted by floodwaters.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 08/10/2023 12:00 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.  
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

Incident Location: Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte
Issue Date: Saturday 07 October 2023, 11:28 am
Next Update: Sunday 08 October 2023, 12:00 pm

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/30688/moreinfo

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte.
- The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging 0 mm in the upper part of the catchment as well as in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Friday 06 October 2023. 
- No rainfall is forecast for the catchment for Saturday 07 October 2023. 
- Water levels of the Yarra River and Watts Rivers at various locations are rising in response to the rain over the past few days. 

Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte:
- The level of the Yarra River at Yarra Glen is currently at 4.53 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (4.10 metres). It peaked at 4.56 metres (close to Moderate Floor Level 4.60 metres) overnight and is now falling very slowly.
- The level of the Yarra River at Christmas Hills is currently at 2.50 metres, below the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres), and rising. It is expected to peak around the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres) later today, Saturday 7th October.
- The level of the Yarra River at Warrandyte is currently at 2.17 metres, below the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres), and rising. It is expected to peak around the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres) later today, Saturday 7th October. 


Act now - take actions immediately to protect your life and property, and move to higher ground.
